             was indicted for <rs id="t18280911-289-off1480" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-off1480" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-off1480" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18280911-289-cd1481" type="crimeDate">25th of August</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-289-off1480 t18280911-289-cd1481"></join>, 4 shillings, and 1 sixpence, the monies of 
                     <persName id="t18280911-289-victim1592" type="victimName">
                        John 
                        Marsden
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-victim1592" type="surname" value="Marsden"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18280911-289-victim1592" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18280911-289-victim1592" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-289-off1480 t18280911-289-victim1592"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JOHN MARSDEN. I lost my money on the 25th of August, about half-past twelve o'clock at noon, from my trousers pocket; I had been at work close by, and went to a field to get my dinner - I laid down on the grass, and fell asleep- I did not see it taken.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-289-person1593">
                  JANE 
                  HAYES
               <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1593" type="surname" value="HAYES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1593" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1593" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My husband and I went to look out at our window, and saw the prisoner lying down on the right side of the prosecutor - he passed his hand several times across his body, took something from his right hand trousers pocket, and put it into his own waistcoat pocket; my husband went down, and took the prisoner just as he was rising from him - I saw 2s. 6d. taken from his pocket.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-289-person1594">
                  ANN 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1594" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1594" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1594" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I heard Mr. Hayes go down; I went out, and saw the prisoner taking something from the prosecutor- I saw him taken, and he threw something away; I went to the place, and picked up two shillings.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-289-person1595">
                  THOMAS 
                  BOLTON
               <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1595" type="surname" value="BOLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1595" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1595" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was at work close by. and saw the prisoner and another loitering about the field nearly three hours - I did not see him take anything, but I heard the cry of Stop thief! I ran and took the prisoner just as the prosecutor got up - the prisoner took 2s. 6d. from his pocket into his hand; we had hard work to get his hand open - officer was forced to hit his knuckles.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-289-person1596">
                  GEORGE 
                  ADAMS
               <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1596" type="surname" value="ADAMS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1596" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1596" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw the prisoner and the witnesses - I came up to them; I took him to Worship-street, and searched him, but found nothing; I saw his hand was clenched when we took him - he would not open his hand, and I threw him down, and threw myself upon him; I beat his hand with my staff till he did open it- there were two shillings and one sixpence in it; the prosecutor swore to the sixpence.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-289-person1597">
                  JOHN 
                  MARSDEN
               <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1597" type="surname" value="MARSDEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1597" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-person1597" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . There is a punch on the reverse side of this sixpence, by which I know it - it was all in my pocket when I went to sleep.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-289-verdict1482" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-289-verdict1482" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 21.</p>
